data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code has **three** breaking patterns in .NET 8:

| API | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (SYSLIB0046 in .NET 9), unreliable | `CancellationToken.WaitHandle` |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | Can't be interrupted by cancellation | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with token |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        WaitHandle[] handles = [_newEvent, token.WaitHandle];

        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny returns index: 0 = new event, 1 = cancellation
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1)
                break; // cancellation requested

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition
            // where rapid Enqueue calls could lose signals)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();          // wakes WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);    // wait for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation
        // guarantees the loop exits at the next WaitAny call
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

1. **`Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`** — The token signals the loop cooperatively; no forcible termination needed.

2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` → `token.WaitHandle`** — `WaitHandle.WaitAny` watches *both* the event and the cancellation handle, so the thread wakes instantly on cancel.

3. **`while (true)` → `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)`** — The loop checks cancellation each iteration.

4. **Bug fix: drain loop** — The original code had a race: two fast `Enqueue` calls → one `Set()` is lost after `Reset()`, leaving an item stuck. The migrated version drains all items per wake-up.

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Keeping `Thread.Abort()` as a "fallback" | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — there is no fallback in .NET 8 |
| Using `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne()` alone | Doesn't also wait on `_newEvent`; use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` for both |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and callbacks — always implement `IDisposable` |
| Forgetting `IsBackground = true` | Without it, the thread keeps the process alive if `Stop()` is never called |

### Further Modernization (Optional)

If you want a fully modern approach, replace the entire manual threading with `Channel<T>`:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _worker;

    public void Start() =>
        _worker = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            Handle(item);
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) =>
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        if (_worker is not null)
            await _worker;
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();
}
```

This eliminates all manual synchronization — no locks, no `WaitHandle`, no explicit `Thread`. The `Channel<T>` approach is idiomatic .NET 8 and handles backpressure, cancellation, and draining automatically.
